          <div class="questions">
            <div class="question glue-mod-spacer-7-bottom">
              <h1
                class="glue-headline glue-headline--headline-4 glue-mod-spacer-1-bottom"
              >
                Whatâ€™s a Community Mobility Report?
              </h1>
              <p class="glue-mod-spacer-2-bottom">
                Each Community Mobility Report is broken down by location and
                displays the change in visits to places like grocery stores and
                parks.
              </p>
              <p class="glue-mod-spacer-2-bottom">
                Weâ€™re working to add more countries, regions and languages in
                the coming weeks. This is an early release and reports will be
                updated regularly.
              </p>
              <img
                src="static/image.png"
                alt="Louisiana's Community Mobility Report shows a 45% decrease in visits to places like restaurants and shopping centers and a 16% decrease in visits to places like groceries and pharmacies since January."
              />
            </div>

            <div class="question glue-mod-spacer-7-bottom">
              <h1
                class="glue-headline glue-headline--headline-4 glue-mod-spacer-1-bottom"
              >
                Preserving privacy
              </h1>
              <p class="glue-mod-spacer-2-bottom">
                The Community Mobility Reports were developed to be helpful
                while adhering to our stringent privacy protocols and protecting
                peopleâ€™s privacy. No personally identifiable information, such
                as an individualâ€™s location, contacts or movement, will be made
                available at any point.
              </p>
              <p class="glue-mod-spacer-2-bottom">
                Insights in these reports are created with aggregated,
                anonymized sets of data from users who have turned on the
                <a href="https://support.google.com/accounts/answer/3118687"
                  >Location History</a
                >
                setting, which is off by default. People who have Location
                History turned on can choose to turn it off at any time from
                their
                <a href="https://myaccount.google.com/activitycontrols"
                  >Google Account</a
                >
                and can always delete Location History data directly from their
                <a href="https://www.google.com/maps/timeline">Timeline</a>.
              </p>
              <p class="glue-mod-spacer-2-bottom">
                We also use the same world-class anonymization technology used
                in our products every day to keep your activity data private and
                secure. This includes
                <a
                  href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FfAdemDkLsc&feature=youtu.be"
                  >differential privacy</a
                >, which adds artificial noise to our datasets, enabling us to
                generate insights while preventing the identification of any
                individual person.
              </p>
              <p class="glue-mod-spacer-2-bottom">
                Visit Google's
                <a href="https://policies.google.com/privacy">Privacy Policy</a>
                to learn more about how we keep your data private, safe and
                secure.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="question">
              <h1
                class="glue-headline glue-headline--headline-4 glue-mod-spacer-1-bottom"
              >
                How long will these reports be available?
              </h1>
              <p class="glue-mod-spacer-2-bottom">
                These reports will be available for a limited time, so long as
                public health officials find them useful in their work to stop
                the spread of COVID-19.
              </p>
              <p class="glue-mod-spacer-2-bottom">
                Learn more about these reports on the
                <a
                  href="https://www.blog.google/technology/health/covid-19-community-mobility-reports"
                  >blog post</a
                >.
              </p>
            </div>
